  <h2>How We Met</h2>

  <p>
    I first crossed paths with Christopher Stanmore-Major through the sailing community in Atlantic Canada. I was the guy with 3D printers looking for problems to solve. He was the guy with a boat and a long list of problems. It was a natural fit.
  </p>

  <p>
    Christopher — CSM to everyone who knows him — is not your typical weekend sailor. He's a blue-water captain with thousands of ocean miles under his keel. He's crossed the Atlantic, raced offshore, and delivered boats up and down the eastern seaboard. Sailing isn't his hobby. It's his life.
  </p>

  <h2>The Sailor</h2>

  <p>
    CSM learned to sail the old way — on the water, in rough conditions, making mistakes and learning from them. He's the kind of sailor who can read weather by looking at the sky, navigate by the stars if the electronics go dark, and fix a broken rig with whatever's on board. He's done it because he's had to.
  </p>

  <p>
    What sets him apart from a lot of experienced sailors I've met is his openness to new technology. Some old-school sailors are skeptical of anything that plugs in. CSM sees tools for what they are — if it makes the boat safer and faster, he's interested. That's why he was immediately intrigued when I started talking about 3D printing custom boat parts.
  </p>

  <p>
    His sailing resume includes offshore races, long-distance cruising, and boat deliveries in conditions that would keep most people at the dock. He's the kind of captain you want making decisions when things go sideways at 3 AM in thirty-knot winds.
  </p>

  <h2>The Newport Bermuda Connection</h2>

  <p>
    The Newport Bermuda Race is one of the oldest and most prestigious ocean races in the world. First run in 1906, it's a 635-nautical-mile sprint from Newport, Rhode Island, to the island of Bermuda. Open ocean, Gulf Stream crossing, unpredictable weather. It's a serious race that demands serious preparation.
  </p>

  <p>
    CSM has had his eye on this race for years. When we started talking about what 3D3D could bring to a campaign like this, things clicked fast. Custom hardware, on-demand replacement parts, rapid prototyping of rigging solutions — all things that matter when you're preparing a boat for offshore racing on a real-world budget.
  </p>

  <p>
    He's not approaching this as a vanity project. CSM runs this campaign like a professional operation — structured, planned, accountable. He manages the boat prep, the crew, the logistics, and the safety planning. My role is the fabrication and technology side.
  </p>

  <h2>Why This Partnership Works</h2>

  <p>
    I'm a mechanic by trade and a maker by obsession. CSM is a sailor and a captain. We come at problems from different angles but we think the same way: figure out what's broken, figure out the simplest fix, execute it, move on.
  </p>

  <p>
    There's no committee. There's no chain of approval. He tells me what the boat needs, I design it and print it, we test it on the water. If it works, it stays. If it doesn't, I redesign it that night and we try again the next day. That loop — need, design, print, test — is exactly what 3D printing was built for.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    The best marine hardware is the hardware that solves a specific problem on a specific boat. Off-the-shelf is a compromise. Custom is the answer.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Beyond the Race</h2>

  <p>
    The Newport Bermuda campaign is the flagship project, but CSM's vision extends beyond a single race. He's interested in proving that small, well-prepared boats with smart technology integration can compete at a level that used to require massive budgets. That modern fabrication tools — especially 3D printing — change the math on what's possible for independent sailors.
  </p>

  <p>
    That resonates with everything 3D3D stands for. We're not a big operation. We don't have sponsors writing six-figure checks. What we have is capability, speed, and the willingness to do things differently.
  </p>

  <p>
    CSM brings the seamanship. I bring the tools. Together, we're building something that I think is going to turn some heads — not just at the finish line, but in how we got there.
  </p>
